In France, voting has traditionally been done in low-technology: voters isolate themselves in a box and put a preprinted piece of paper indicating their choice of candidate in an envelope.
Once officials have verified the identity of the electorate, the electorate puts the envelope in the ballot box and signs the voting list.
The procedure is codified very precisely in the French electoral law.
Since 1988, ballots have been transparent, so that voters and observers can see that the urns do not contain ballots at the start of the vote and that no other ballots are added than those that are called and come from approved voters.
Candidates can send representatives as witnesses to all parts of the process. In the evening, the votes of volunteers are counted under sharp supervision and after specific procedures.
