When a small group of living beings (a small population) is separated from the main population they came from (as if they move across a mountain range or a river, or if they move to a new island, so that they cannot easily move back), they will often be in a different environment than they were before.
This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population needs to have other functions or adaptations to be a stronger competitor than was previously needed.
The original population has not changed at all; it still needs the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to their new environment, they begin to look like the rest of the population less and less.
Eventually, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process species formation, which simply means the formation of new species.
