Technological determinism is a term that includes a wide range of ideas in practice from technology as a driving force or technological necessity, to a narrow idea that human destiny is driven by an underlying logic that is connected to scientific laws, and the way they are implemented in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a route largely outside of cultural or political influence, and that technology in turn out to have an "impact" on society that is hereditary and not social.
For example, it can say that the motor car necessarily leads to the development of roads.
But a nationwide road network is not economically profitable for just a handful of cars, so that new production methods are developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
When many own cars, there are also more accidents on the roads, leading to inventions of new techniques in the field of health to entire body injuries.
