Out on the savannah, it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system like humans to satisfy his need for amino acids from available plant sources.
In addition, there are serious consequences of non-compliance: reduced growth, malnutrition and ultimately death.
The most readily available plant resources would have been the proteins that exist in leaves and legumes, but for primates like us, these are hard to digest unless they are prepared.
Conversely, animal feed (acers, thermals, eggs) is not only easy to digest; it also provides large amounts of protein, which contains all the essential amino acids.
All in all, it should not surprise us if our own ancestors solved their "protein problem" in roughly the same way as chimpanzees on the savannah do today.
