The Oyapock River Bridge is a cable car bridge that stretches across the Oyapock River and connects the cities of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges de l'Oyapock in French Guiana.
The two towers are 83 meters tall, the bridge is 378 meters long and has two lanes that are 3.50 m wide.
The vertical clearance under the bridge is 15 meters. The building was completed in August 2011. It first opened for traffic in March 2017.
The bridge is scheduled to be fully operational in September 2017 when the Brazilian customs control posts are expected to be completed.
The Guaranís were the most important group of natives living in the area now eastern Paraguay, and they lived as semi-nomadic hunters who also farmed to survive.
The Chaco region was home to other groups of indigenous tribes such as the Guaycurús and the Payaguás, who survived by hunting, collecting and fishing.
Paraguay, formerly known as the “Great Province of India”, came into the world in the 16th century as a result of the meeting of Spanish conquistadors and the native population groups.
The Spanish began the period of colonization that lasted for three centuries.
