Japanese work culture is more hierarchical and formal than what Westerners are accustomed to.
Suits are standard business clothing, and colleagues appeal to each other by their surname or job titles.
Harmony in the workplace is important, and thus emphasizes group effort rather than praise of individual performance.
Workers often need to have their superiors approve of all decisions they make, and they are expected to obey the instructions of their superior without asking questions.
